title: For Trade:  SP101 .357 Magnum package
postcontent:
This magnum came into my life brand new in early 1992, as my first handgun. For the first 10 years or so, it was my primary carry gun, and saw a great deal of action. Primarily, I fired 38Spl from it, because I was never very good with magnums in it.

Since then, it has mostly chilled in various nightstands and storage rooms, with occasional trips to the range, or a run around town. I would estimate the round count is no more than 5k - 99% of it was 38Spl.

The hammer was bobbed early in its life, back when Ruger didn't make a spurless SP. I think the gunsmith contoured it very nicely to preserve as much hammer mass and thickness as possible.

Just recently, I had the HiViz sight put on it, which is great. The springs are all original, and over the years, the action has become lighter and smoother with use, but not as light as Wolff.

Somewhere over the years, the little pin Ruger gave to use for disassembly got away, but I always liked using a little nail more for that anyway.

*The holster is a custom-fit Milt Sparks IWB. I think they called it the "Summer Comfort" model or something. 
*The speedloaders are Safariland push-release, which are PERFECT for quick reloads. *The holders are also Safariland, and are like new. 
*The spare grip is Hogue Monogrip.
 More pics availabe upon request. I have the manual, but the box was cardboard back then, and I discarded it.

If you get the ammo, there are:
*6 Silver Glasers 38Spl+P 
*15 Federal Hi-Shok 125gr HP 357Mag
*30 Federal HP 357Mag of unknown weight
*150 of Georgia Arms 38Spl 158gr FMJ-SWC
*15 Corbon 38Spl+P+ 115gr (These were very hot 38 +P+ loads Corbon used to make in the 90's. The current ones are not that hot. It's almost a magnum round.)

This excellent revolver never failed me, and means a lot to me for sentimental, personal reasons. However, I never used its full magnum potential, have too many guns, want to try new ones, and don't like to form attachments to things. So, it's time to let this trusty friend move on to new adventures...
